    date: "Tuesday, 09/19/2023",
    desc: "The East Ferry Warren: United by Dreams &amp; Design tour and panel discussion will highlight the work of Detroit Future City with residents and non-profits in the East Ferry Warren community to develop and implement a community-driven neighborhood green space vision.<br><br>\nThe East Ferry Warren neighborhood has seen population loss and disinvestment by the public and private sectors over the last 30 years, leaving residents to create a community transformation of their own. This revitalization is centered on the dreams of the community to be a place of joy and peace. This event will highlight the collaborative process undertaken in developing the visioning plan and provide a tour of green space projects from the plan.<br><br>\n\n<strong>Event Details</strong><br>\nTuesday, September 19 <br>\n4:00 pm - 6:15pm Two WalkingTours<br>\n6:30 pm - 8:00pm Panel Discussion at Hunt Street Station<br><br>\n\n\n\nTour highlights include:<br>\n• Arboretum Detroit<br>\n• Callahan Meadow<br>\n• Field Temple<br>\n• Green Loop Pathway<br>\n• Oxygen Alley<br><br><br>\n\n\nThe panel discussion will feature local community-based land leaders with Oakland Avenue Urban Farms and the Bailey Park Neighborhood Development Corporation alongside local planners. Panelists will share insights into the process of designing an inclusive community-driven land use vision along with the challenges and successes faced by the community to make the plan a reality.<br><br>\n\n\n<strong>About Detroit Future City</strong><br>\nDetroit Future City (DFC) is a think tank, policy advocate, and innovation engine developing data-driven strategies to create a more equitable and sustainable future for Detroit. It was established as a non-profit organization in 2015 to catalyze implementation of the Detroit Strategic Framework, a 50-year vision for the City of Detroit developed with input from over 100,000 residents. Through the shared vision of the Detroit Strategic Framework, DFC is committed to advancing the quality of life for all Detroiters. Their role is to steward equitable implementation of the Framework recommendations by providing accessible information to Detroiters, informing and guiding decision-makers’ initiatives and projects, and convening a broad range of stakeholders to better coordinate and align their work.",
